Execution Module

Operational delivery engine.
Milestone-weighted progress system.
Ledger-bound completion authority.
Atomic bridge into verification.

This module does not “track work.”

It defines when work becomes truth.

Core Principle

Execution progress is derived.
Execution completion is constitutional.
Verification must begin atomically.

Execution is not a UI stage.
It is a lifecycle boundary backed by ledger causality.

Domain Responsibilities

This module owns:

Execution creation

Milestone-based weighted progress

Execution completion authority

Evidence enforcement before completion

Ledger-bound EXECUTION\_\* events

Automatic verification initialization

Deterministic progress read model

Non-authoritative progress notes

It does not:

Mutate CaseLifecycle directly

Authorize disbursement

Decide verification outcome

Store derived percent fields

Trust client-supplied progress claims

Execution State Model

ExecutionStatus:

IN_PROGRESS

COMPLETED

ABORTED

Completion is not cosmetic.

It triggers governance.

Starting Execution

startExecution()

Transaction-bound.

Guarantees:

Case exists and not archived

Tenant isolation

Idempotent creation (one execution per case)

Milestones seeded atomically

Ledger event: EXECUTION_STARTED

Milestones are seeded intentionally.

Execution progress is milestone-truth driven.

Milestone System

Each milestone has:

weight

completedAt

completedByUserId

Progress is derived from:

sum(completed.weight) / sum(all.weight)

Never store percentage directly.

Why?

Because stored aggregates drift under:

retries

concurrent updates

partial failures

schema evolution

Truth must be reconstructible.

Completing a Milestone

CompleteMilestoneService.complete()

Transaction guarantees:

Milestone exists

Tenant boundary enforced

Idempotency respected

Execution is IN_PROGRESS

Milestone updated

Ledger event: EXECUTION_PROGRESS_RECORDED

Recalculate weighted progress

If 100% → execution auto-completes

Ledger event: EXECUTION_COMPLETED

Execution completion emerges from milestone truth.

It is not manually toggled.

Execution Completion

Two possible completion paths:

Automatic (100% milestone weight)

Explicit via completeExecution()

Both paths:

Enforce invariants

Append ledger event

Remain atomic

Constitutional Completion Boundary

completeExecution()

This is a lifecycle-grade boundary.

Preconditions:

Execution exists

Not already COMPLETED (idempotent)

Not ABORTED

Evidence must exist

Evidence validation enforced via:

assertExecutionEvidenceSatisfied()

If no evidence → invariant violation.

No silent completion.

Evidence Policy

assertExecutionEvidenceSatisfied()

Transaction-safe count query.

Completion requires:

≥ 1 evidence attached to timeline entries of case.

This invariant ensures:

Work is documented

Completion is auditable

Governance does not drift

Evidence is a lifecycle gate, not a UI hint.

Atomic Bridge to Verification

After EXECUTION_COMPLETED:

initializeVerification() runs inside the same transaction.

Guarantees:

No execution completes without verification initialized

No orphan verification records

Ledger event: VERIFICATION_STARTED

Idempotent behavior

This protects lifecycle determinism.

Execution → Verification is atomic.

Derived Progress Model

ExecutionProgressService.getProgress()

Pure read model.

Derives:

totalWeight

completedWeight

percent (rounded)

derivedStatus

milestone presentation

DerivedStatus is computed.

Database execution.status should match.

UI must trust derived truth, not stored guess.

Non-Authoritative Progress Events

recordExecutionProgress()

Used for:

CHECKPOINT

NOTE

BLOCKED

RESUMED

EVIDENCE_ATTACHED

These do not mutate execution status.

They are operational annotations.

They exist for observability, not governance.

Ledger Events Emitted

EXECUTION_STARTED

EXECUTION_PROGRESS_RECORDED

EXECUTION_COMPLETED

All inside same transaction as state mutation.

Ledger is canonical.

Execution table is projection.

Invariants (Non-Negotiable)

Execution cannot complete without evidence.

ABORTED execution cannot be completed.

Progress percentage must be derived.

Tenant boundary enforced on every read/write.

Milestone completion must be idempotent.

Ledger event must exist for every authoritative state change.

Verification must initialize atomically after completion.

Break these and lifecycle replay becomes inconsistent.

Concurrency Protections

Transaction boundary protects:

Double milestone completion

Duplicate execution creation

Partial completion without ledger

Race conditions in weighted progress

Idempotency keys protect:

Replay-safe milestone completion

Traceable authority proofs

Duplicate ledger write prevention

Execution remains deterministic under load.

Failure Modes Considered

Duplicate milestone completion
→ Idempotent return

Concurrent milestone completion
→ Transaction isolation protects

Execution crash mid-completion
→ Transaction rollback

Completion without evidence
→ InvariantViolationError

Verification initialization failure
→ Entire transaction rolls back

Ledger failure
→ No execution completion occurs

Scalability Characteristics

Current complexity:

Progress derivation: O(n milestones)

Completion recalculation: O(n milestones)

Evidence check: O(1) count query

Future optimization options:

Aggregated progress column (validated)

Aggregate SQL query instead of in-memory reduce

Partial index on (caseId, tenantId)

SELECT FOR UPDATE on milestone row if contention increases

Do not prematurely optimize.

Correctness > micro-efficiency.

Why Percent Is Not Stored

Storing derived percent:

Introduces reconciliation drift

Requires repair jobs

Breaks replay determinism

Complicates audit

Derived state keeps system honest.

Ledger + milestones reconstruct everything.

Observability Expectations

Every authoritative transition must produce:

Ledger event

Authority proof

Actor identity

Progress labels are optional.
Lifecycle transitions are not.

Mental Model

Execution is a delivery contract.

Milestones are atomic commitments.
Completion is constitutional.
Verification is automatic.

This module ensures:

Work is measurable.
Completion is defensible.
Governance remains replay-safe.

If someone audits this system five years from now,
they must be able to replay execution from immutable events
and derive the same truth.

That is the bar.
